<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">
power to call a special shareowner meeting (or the closest percentage to 10% according to state law) without the current requirement to petition a court in order to do so. This proposal does not
impact our board&#146;s current power to call a special meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Exxon Mobil is in a small minority of companies that require shareholders to go to court in order
to call for a special shareholder meeting. Plus Exxon Mobil may have an unlimited budget to oppose such a request in court and shareholders do not have such a budget. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Special meetings allow shareowners to vote on important matters, such as electing new directors that can arise between annual meetings. This proposal topic won more
than 70%-support at Edwards Lifesciences and SunEdison in 2013. This 70%-support would have been higher if all shareholders had access to independent proxy voting advice. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">A shareholder ability to call a special meeting would put shareholders in a better position to give continuing input on improving the makeup of our board of directors.
This topic is more importance since we do not have any oversight of our CEO by an independent Board Chairman. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Mark Zuckerberg, Jeff Immelt and Elon Musk are
examples of problems with concentrating too much power in one person. Darren Woods, our CEO/Chairman received the highest negative votes of any Exxon Mobil director in 2018. And Exxon Mobil executive pay received only a 73%-vote in 2018 compared to
90% and 95% votes at many companies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Plus we apparently do not have a Lead Director as this title does not even appear in our 2018 proxy. Meanwhile in the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">5-years</FONT> leading up to the submittal of this proposal our stock fell from $101 to $77. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Also our right to shareholder proxy access
may be unreachable because it can only be used by 20 shareholders who have owned a total of $30&nbsp;billion of Exxon Mobil stock continuously for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">3-years.</FONT> If a group of 20 shareholders needs one more
shareholder to meet this enormous $30&nbsp;billion requirement &#150; the group is totally out of luck. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial" ALIGN="center">Please vote yes: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial" ALIGN="center"><B>Special Shareholder Meeting &#150; Proposal 5</B>&#148;<B> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you vote AGAINST this proposal for the following reasons: </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Board believes it is important that shareholders have a meaningful right to call special shareholder meetings, a right that ExxonMobil currently provides. A special
meeting of ExxonMobil shareholders may be called by holders of not less than 10&nbsp;percent of outstanding shares, in accordance with New Jersey law, upon a showing of good cause. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">By requiring a showing of good cause to call a special meeting, New Jersey law, applicable to our Company, effectively balances the interests of all shareholders. By
allowing shareholders of at least 10&nbsp;percent of outstanding common stock to call a meeting for an appropriate purpose, all shareholders are protected against the potential risk that a minority shareholder group abuses this right for an
illegitimate objective. If, after engagement with shareholders, the Board of Directors agrees that a special meeting is needed, then a meeting could be scheduled by the Board without the need for a court review. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Shareholder interests are protected by a strong, independent Board that is responsible for the effective oversight of management, including the CEO. Effective
leadership is further provided by the independent Presiding Director who holds the authority to call, chair, and determine the agenda for executive sessions of the independent directors; provide feedback to the Chairman; chair Board meetings in the
absence of the Chairman; and in consultation with the Chairman, review schedules and agendas for Board meetings. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Shareholders recognized the strength, leadership,
and overwhelming independence of the ExxonMobil Board by providing voting support of more than 95&nbsp;percent for all ExxonMobil directors in 2018. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Many companies that provide shareholders the right to call a special shareholder meeting do so at a higher share
threshold, often 20&nbsp;percent or higher. As such, the 10&nbsp;percent threshold coupled with the good cause requirement provides a meaningful and balanced shareholder right. The Board believes this proposal is, therefore, unnecessary. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:arial"><B><A NAME="toc686227_18"></A>Item 6&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Board Matrix </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">This
proposal was submitted by the New York City Retirement Systems, 1 Centre Street, 8<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> Floor North, New York, NY 10007, the beneficial holder of 5,817,212 shares. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">&#147;RESOLVED<B>:</B> Shareholders of Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#145;Exxon&#146;) request that its Board of Directors (the &#145;Board&#146;) disclose to shareholders
each director&#146;s/nominee&#146;s gender and race/ethnicity, as well as skills, experiences and attributes that are most relevant in light of Exxon&#146;s overall business, long-term strategy and risks, presented in a matrix form. The requested
matrix shall not include any attributes the Board identifies as minimum qualifications for all Board candidates in compliance with SEC Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K.</FONT> </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The requested matrix shall be presented to shareholders in Exxon&#146;s annual proxy statement and on its website within six months of the date of the annual meeting,
and updated annually. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B></B>SUPPORTING STATEMENT<B> </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We believe a diverse
board &#150; in terms of relevant skills and experience AND gender and race/ethnicity &#150; is a good indicator of a well-functioning board. Diverse boards can better manage risk by avoiding &#145;groupthink&#146; &#150; a cognitive bias whereby
&#145;homogenous, cohesive groups&#146; tend toward standard agreement with known business associates and not challenge &#145;basic premises&#146; (<U>http://www.ieoimf.org/ieo/files/completedevaluations/01102011Crisis_IV._Why_
Did_the_IMF_Fail_to_Give_Clear_Warning.pdf</U>). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">McKinsey research suggests that companies with greater gender and ethnic board diversity have stronger financial
performance (<U><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/organization/our-insights/why-diversity-matters</FONT></FONT></U>). MSCI research suggests that gender diverse boards have
fewer instances of bribery, corruption, and fraud (<U>https://www.msci.com/documents/10199/04b6f646-d638-4878-9c61-4eb91748a82b</U>). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Many directors recognize the
importance of, and many boards disclose information on, gender and racial/ethnic diversity on boards: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt">According to a 2017 PwC survey of 886 directors, 68% believe gender diversity is very important and 42% believe racial
diversity is very important. Among those who responded that diversity is important, 82% said it improved board performance and 59% said it improved company performance. (<U>https://www.pwc.com/us/en/ <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">governance-insights-center/annual-corporate-directors-survey/assets/pwc-2017-annual-corporate--directors--survey.pdf</FONT></FONT></U>) </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt">According to a 2017 Equilar study of 500 large companies, 45.1% disclosed board composition by gender and 39.8% disclosed
composition by race or ethnicity.
(<U><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">http://semlerbrossy.com/wp-content/uploads/Equilar-Board-Composition-and-Director-Recruiting-Trends-SEP-2017.pdf
</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></U>) </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">In its 2018 proxy statement, Exxon fails to disclose individual directors&#146; individual
qualifications in a matrix format, to provide an overview of how the board effectively fulfills its oversight responsibilities in the aggregate. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">A Board matrix
will give Exxon shareholders a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#145;big-picture&#146;</FONT> view of nominees&#146; attributes, both individually and collectively, and how they fit together, thereby enabling shareholders to (a)&nbsp;assess how
well-suited individual director nominees are for the company in light of (i)&nbsp;the company&#146;s evolving business strategy and risks and (ii)&nbsp;the overall mix of skills and experiences; (b)&nbsp;identify any gaps in skills, experience or
other characteristics; and (c)&nbsp;make better informed proxy voting decisions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Using a matrix to present director qualifications is recommended by the National
Association of Corporate Directors (<U>https://www.nacdonline.org/Resources/Article.cfm?ItemNumber=35337</U>), among other groups. The EY Center for Board Matters reported that 29% of S&amp;P 500 companies disclosed a director skills matrix in 2018
(<U><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">https://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/EY-cbm-proxy-season-review-2018/$FILE/EY-cbm-proxy-season-review-2018.pdf
</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT></U>). </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="right">61</TD>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The matrix approach that we request is consistent with the request in a March 2015 rulemaking petition to the
Securities and Exchange Commission seeking mandatory matrix disclosure by all U.S. public companies (<U><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">https://www.sec.gov/rules/petitions/2015/petn4-682.pdf</FONT></U>). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We urge shareholders to vote FOR this proposal.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you
vote AGAINST this proposal for the following reasons: </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Board agrees that diversity is a key attribute of a well-functioning board, and is important
information for shareholders. This is one of the reasons we provide detailed information regarding our Board in our proxy statement and on our website. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">After
conferring with the proponent, we supplemented this year&#146;s proxy statement with several enhancements, including: a detailed matrix allowing shareholders to easily judge the collective competencies of the Board; clarity between Board
qualifications and the competencies sought for director candidates; descriptions of the relevance of each competency to ExxonMobil&#146;s business; infographics related to gender, race/ethnicity, and age diversity; and relevant competencies shown in
each director biography. This adds to the data traditionally provided, including lists of the qualifications and competencies sought by the Board and a detailed description of how diversity fits into the candidate search process. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The board refreshment process is a key function of the Board and a priority of the Board Affairs Committee. This committee engages an independent executive search firm
to help identify new director candidates, and also considers recommendations made by employee directors, shareholders, and others. All recommendations are evaluated against the Board&#146;s Guidelines for Selection of
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Employee</FONT> Directors; these guidelines are available on <I>exxonmobil.com</I> and summarized in our proxy statement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Diversity of experiences and backgrounds are important considerations in identifying and assessing Board candidates. The success of our refreshment program is clearly
evident in the results. Female members comprise 30&nbsp;percent of our Board, well above the S&amp;P 500 average of 24&nbsp;percent (<I>2018 Spencer Stuart Board Index</I>). The Board&#146;s minority representation of 20&nbsp;percent also exceeds
the average of the top 200 S&amp;P 500 companies (<I>2018 Spencer Stuart Board Index</I>). Four of the last seven most recently elected independent directors were women or race/ethnic minorities. Our Board also enjoys significant shareholder
support, with votes on average ranging well into the mid <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">90-percentile</FONT> over the past 10 years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The imposition of a
prescriptive matrix by individual director can promote a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">check-the-box</FONT></FONT> approach to refreshment, thus increasing the risk of bypassing a well-qualified candidate, and may
mislead shareholders into wrongly believing that only a subset of directors contribute to particular decisions or represent the Board on particular matters.&nbsp;Instead, the Board acts as a collective body, representing the interests of all
shareholders. While individual directors leverage their experience and knowledge, Board decisions and perspectives reflect the collective wisdom of the group. The breadth of our disclosures, including the enhancements mentioned above, emphasizes the
collective strength of our Board and meaningfully addresses the proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:arial"><B><A NAME="toc686227_19"></A>Item&nbsp;7&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Climate Change Board Committee
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">This proposal was submitted by Adam Seitchik, a client of Arjuna Capital, 1 Elm Street, Manchester, MA 01944, the beneficial owner of 42 shares. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">&#147;<B>RESOLVED:</B> Shareholders request the Board of Directors charter a new Board Committee on Climate Change to evaluate Exxon Mobil&#146;s strategic vision and
responses to climate change, and better inform Board decision making on climate issues. The charter should explicitly require the committee to engage in formal review and oversight of corporate strategy, above and beyond matters of legal compliance,
to assess the company&#146;s responses to climate related risks and opportunities, including the potential impacts of climate change on business, strategy, financial planning, and the environment. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%"></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.10em; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">62&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="right">


<IMG SRC="g686227g34r14.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Supporting Statement: </B>The proponent believes an independent committee would better provide focused fiduciary
oversight of climate related risks and opportunities and should include board members with climate change expertise in areas such as policy, carbon pricing, renewable energy, adaptation, and climate science. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>WHEREAS:</B> Major oil companies face unprecedented disruption to their business driven by global imperatives to limit global warming and competition from <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-carbon-emitting</FONT> technologies. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change projects dramatic drops in industry emissions of 50 to 90&nbsp;percent by 2050 are necessary to limit global warming to between 1.5 and
2 degrees Celsius. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Board oversight of climate change strategy and planning is essential to address the existential threat of climate change to the fossil fuel
industry and our Company. 84&nbsp;percent of companies in the energy sector have adopted some level of board oversight of climate change, but only 6&nbsp;percent provide board incentives (monetary and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-monetary)</FONT> for managing this critical threat, the lowest of all industries. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Effective governance of climate change risk,
opportunity, adaptation and transition is essential to the long term success of Exxon. Investors believe a commitment to good climate change governance should be formalized in the board charter. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">As fiduciaries, our Board is responsible for stewardship of business performance and long term strategic plans, while reviewing specific risk factors like developments
in climate science and policy. Evidence from other companies demonstrates that committee charter language helps define the scope of fiduciary duties of board members. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Currently, there is no specialized committee to help the Board carry out its responsibility for Climate Change oversight like there is for the Audit, Board Affairs,
Compensation, Public Issues and Contributions, and Finance Committees, despite the existential nature of climate change for our Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Exxon has stated that
&#145;climate risk oversight ultimately is the responsibility of the Board of Directors,&#146; yet climate appears a tangential focus of the full board, as it is among approximately 17 other duties. And despite reporting that the Public Issues and
Contributions Committee assists in oversight of climate risk, the committee&#146;s charter does not list climate change among its approximately 6 other duties. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">A
failure to adequately plan for a low carbon transition, including climate change policy, competition from renewables, peak oil demand, and unburnable fossil fuel reserves, may place investor capital at substantial risk. It vital that our Company
formalize board level oversight of climate change strategy to remain successful in an increasingly decarbonizing economy.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you vote
AGAINST this proposal for the following reasons: </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Board agrees that oversight of risks and the Company&#146;s strategic direction is an important aspect of
ExxonMobil&#146;s enterprise risk management, and that effective risk management is essential to the long-term success of the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Board is responsible for
the oversight of all Company risks, including climate-related risks. As part of a well-established process, the Board routinely reviews environmental stewardship through briefings on scientific and technical research, public policy positions and
analysis, and Company initiatives and actions. The Board recognizes that the risk of climate change has the potential to manifest itself in a number of ways. The risk of changing demand for ExxonMobil&#146;s products for any reason, including
climate, technology, or economic conditions, is considered a key risk, which is managed by the full Board. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">To understand the potential corporate impact of a
specific risk factor, it is important to understand the interactions and interdependencies with other risk drivers. As such, the Board believes it is important to evaluate specific risks in the context of all relevant risk. Annually, through its
review of the <I>Outlook for Energy</I>, areas of research and development and the Company&#146;s strategies and business plans, the Board assesses the Company&#146;s management of, and response to, external risk factors.&nbsp;As part of its careful
consideration of climate-related risks and opportunities, for the last decade at least one session of the full Board each year is dedicated to climate issues, with the Board engaging Company subject matter experts on the latest developments in
climate science and policy. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">In addition, the Board relies on committees to provide additional insight on the risks faced by the Company. For
example, the Board Audit Committee assesses ExxonMobil&#146;s overall risk management approach and structure to ensure that enterprise-level risks are being appropriately considered by the Board. The Public Issues and Contributions Committee
(&#147;PICC&#148;) regularly reviews ExxonMobil&#146;s safety, health, and environmental performance, including steps taken to identify and manage climate-related risks and opportunities, and informs the Board on such matters. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The PICC, in conjunction with the Audit Committee, assists the Board in regularly considering climate-related risks, including the potential impacts on business,
strategy, financial planning, and the environment, in a multitude of settings. These include: during the annual corporate planning process; during technology reviews; when reviewing current events; during shareholder engagements; when assessing
Company performance; during annual visits to operating sites; and in reviews of publications like the <I>Energy</I><I></I><I>&nbsp;&amp; Carbon Summary</I> and <I>Outlook for Energy</I>; and regulatory filings like the SEC Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K.</FONT> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Accordingly, the Board believes that the PICC, and the Audit Committee in its review of the risk management framework, are
better structured to assess the risks of climate change and make recommendations to the Board than a new committee created solely for this purpose. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Thus, while we
agree that effective governance and oversight of climate issues are critical to long-term success, given the already-established review process, as well as the broad oversight currently provided by the PICC, the Audit Committee, and the full Board,
the Board is confident that this matter is appropriately addressed. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:arial"><B><A NAME="toc686227_25"></A>Item&nbsp;8 &#150; Report on Risks of Gulf Coast Petrochemical
Investments </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">This proposal was submitted by Andrew Behar, a client of As You Sow, 1611 Telegraph Avenue, Suite 1450, Oakland, CA 94612, the beneficial owner 40
shares. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">&#147;<B>RESOLVED</B>: Shareholders request that ExxonMobil, with board oversight, publish a report, omitting proprietary information and prepared at
reasonable cost, assessing the public health risks of expanding petrochemical operations and investments in areas increasingly prone to climate change-induced storms, flooding, and sea level rise. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Supporting Statement</B>: Investors request the company assess, among other related issues at management and Board discretion: The adequacy of measures the company
is employing to prevent public health impacts from associated chemical releases. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>WHEREAS</B>: Investors are concerned about the financial, health,
environmental, and reputational risks associated with operating and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">building-out</FONT> new chemical plants and related infrastructure in Gulf Coast locations increasingly prone to catastrophic storms and flooding
associated with climate change. Civil society groups have mobilized to oppose the expansion of petrochemical facilities in their communities due to concerns regarding direct impacts to their health and livelihoods from unintentional air and water
pollutant releases. Such opposition threatens to jeopardize ExxonMobil&#146;s social license to operate in the region. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Petrochemical facilities like ethane crackers
and polyethylene processing plants produce dangerous pollutants including benzene (a known carcinogen), Volatile Organic Compounds, and sulfur dioxide. These operations can become inundated and pose severe chemical release risks during extreme
weather events. Flooding from Hurricane Harvey in 2017 resulted in ExxonMobil plant shut downs and the release of unpermitted, unsafe levels of pollutants. Nearby Houston residents reported respiratory and skin problems following ExxonMobil&#146;s
releases during Hurricane Harvey. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Growing storms and the costs they bring our company are predicted to increase in frequency and intensity as global warming
escalates. Flood-related damage is projected to be highest in Texas, where many of ExxonMobil&#146;s petrochemical plants are concentrated. Houston alone has seen three <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">500-year</FONT> floods in the span of three
years. Hurricane Harvey contributed to decreased earnings of approximately $40&nbsp;million for ExxonMobil in 2017. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:arial narrow; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.10em; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">64&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="right">


<IMG SRC="g686227g34r14.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"><I>2019 Proxy Statement</I></TD></TR></TABLE>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Historically, releases from ExxonMobil&#146;s petrochemical operations have exceeded legal limits, exposing the
company to liability and millions in payment for violations of environmental laws including the Clean Air and Clean Water Acts. As climate change intensifies flooding and storm strength, the potential for unplanned chemical releases grows. Investors
are concerned that ExxonMobil has not adequately demonstrated how it will prevent such unsafe chemical releases. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">In spite of these risks, Exxon has accelerated its
petrochemical activity in the Gulf Coast, investing heavily in further expansion in flood-prone areas of Texas and Louisiana. The company has generally disclosed that risks from storms may impact its business and that extreme storms are among the
factors considered in its Operations Integrity Management System. The impacts to Exxon&#146;s operations from Hurricane Harvey, however, indicate the company&#146;s level of preparedness was insufficient. While the Company rapidly expands its
petrochemical assets in climate-impacted areas, its available disclosures do not provide investors adequate information to understand whether ExxonMobil is effectively assessing and managing the drastic increase in material public health and
financial risks presented by climate-related storm impacts and sea level rise.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you vote AGAINST this proposal for the following
reasons: </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil invests only in petrochemical plants or other operations where the potential public health risk can be managed to safe and acceptable
levels. Therefore, the report requested by the proponent is not necessary. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">To meet society&#146;s growing demand for our products, ExxonMobil must often work in
remote and challenging environments all over the world, including in flood-prone areas. Using a rigorous and comprehensive assessment process, we consider the full range of potential environmental, socioeconomic, and health risks associated with our
operations before we begin a new development. This allows us to establish a comprehensive understanding of the potential impacts and develop measures to avoid, mitigate, or remedy them. This proven assessment approach is worked jointly with the
communities in which we operate and in cooperation with the governments and agencies that provide oversight for permit application and approval processes. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil&#146;s <I>Operations Integrity Management System (&#147;OIMS&#148;)</I> has proven effective at ensuring readiness for and resiliency to extreme weather
conditions. Our facilities are designed, constructed, and operated consistent with industry standards to withstand a variety of extreme weather and environmental conditions. When considering physical risks such as flooding and storms, we use
historical experience, with additional safety factors, to cover a range of uncertainties. We monitor and manage ongoing facility integrity, and maintain disaster preparedness, response, and business continuity plans. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Our scientists and engineers are considered experts and through their participation in industry groups, they advise and gather insights to inform and improve standards,
which in turn are adopted to enhance ExxonMobil&#146;s operations. ExxonMobil&#146;s spill prevention program and related procedures are effective. We build layers of protection by requiring that equipment is inspected and maintained, operators are
trained, and drills are conducted. We take a rigorous approach to assessing and managing the potential impacts of a spill on water or land, with a particular emphasis on risk management, operations integrity, and containment capabilities. If a spill
does occur, we ensure a rapid, comprehensive response to minimize the impact on communities and the environment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">These detailed, well-practiced, and continuously
evaluated emergency response plans, tailored to each facility, help ExxonMobil respond to unplanned events, including extreme weather. For example, we started response efforts to Hurricane Harvey before the storm even arrived, safely shutting down
operations, and quickly recovering after it passed. Our Baytown and Beaumont refineries effectively minimized environmental impacts from our operations as a result of the storm and the resulting power loss. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Our efforts benefit our operations and the communities where we operate. At Beaumont, ExxonMobil assisted in emergency storm recovery with <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">around-the-clock</FONT></FONT> efforts to restore water service to the city by mobilizing a temporary pumping solution, providing numerous generators for critical storm water management
systems, and providing <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-kind</FONT> donations of labor and key equipment exceeding an estimated $900,000. At Baytown, the Company donated 27,000 gallons of fuel to area first responders, delivered cleaning supplies
to schools and partnering agencies, and provided much-needed supplies to local schools. In the Portland, Texas area, ExxonMobil redirected the Company&#146;s heavy equipment and local crews to assist with recovery efforts, removing 2,400 tons of
debris. Prior to the storm&#146;s arrival, ExxonMobil also made a financial contribution to community disaster relief efforts. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil reports on <I>OIMS,</I> process safety, and environmental performance at its facilities in our
<I>Sustainability Report</I> and other public statements and publications<I>, </I>available at <I>exxonmobil.com</I>. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:arial"><B><A NAME="toc686227_27"></A>Item&nbsp;9
&#150; Report on Political Contributions </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">This proposal was submitted by the Unitarian Universalist Association, 24 Farnsworth Street, Boston, MA 02210, the
beneficial owners of 87 shares and lead proponent of a filing group. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">&#147;<B>Resolved</B>: The shareholders of Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#145;Exxon&#146; or
&#145;Company&#146;) hereby request that the Company prepare and semiannually update a report, which shall be presented to the pertinent board of directors committee and posted on the Company&#146;s website, that discloses the Company&#146;s: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(a)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial; " ALIGN="left">Policies and procedures for making electoral contributions and expenditures with corporate funds (both direct and
indirect), including the board&#146;s role (if any) in that process; and </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(b)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial; " ALIGN="left">Monetary and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-monetary</FONT> contributions or expenditures that could not be
deducted as an &#145;ordinary and necessary&#146; business expense under section 162(e)(1)(B) of the Internal Revenue Code, including (but not limited to) contributions or expenditures on behalf of candidates, parties, and committees and entities
organized and operating under section 501(c)(4) of the Internal Revenue Code, as well as the portion of any dues or payments made to any <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-exempt</FONT> organization (such as a trade association) used for an
expenditure or contribution that, if made directly by the Company, would not be deductible under section 162(e)(1)(B) of the Internal Revenue Code. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The report shall be made available within 12 months of the annual meeting and identify all recipients and the amount paid to each recipient from Company funds. This
proposal does not encompass lobbying spending. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial" ALIGN="center"><B>Supporting Statement </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">As long-term Exxon shareholders, we support transparency and accountability in corporate electoral spending. Disclosure is in the best interest of the Company and its
shareholders. The Supreme Court recognized this in its 2010 Citizens United decision, which said: &#145;[D]isclosure permits citizens and shareholders to react to the speech of corporate entities in a proper way. This transparency enables the
electorate to make informed decisions and give proper weight to different speakers and messages.&#146; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Publicly available records show Exxon has contributed at
least $11,500,000 in corporate funds since the 2010 election cycle. (CQMoneyLine: <U>http://moneyline.cq.com</U>; National Institute on Money in State Politics: <U>http://www.followthemoney.org</U>). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We acknowledge that Exxon publicly discloses a policy on corporate political spending and its direct contributions to candidates, parties, and committees. However, we
believe this is insufficient because Exxon does not disclose the following: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt">A full list of trade associations to which it belongs and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-deductible</FONT>
portions under section 162(e)(1)(B) of the dues paid to each; and </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt">Payments to any other third-party organization, including those organized under section 501(c)(4) of the Internal Revenue
Code, that could be used for election-related purposes. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Information on indirect electoral spending through trade associations and 501(c)(4)
groups cannot be obtained by shareholders unless the Company discloses it. This proposal asks the Company to disclose all of its electoral spending, both direct and indirect. This would bring our company in line with a growing number of leading
companies, including <B>ConocoPhillips</B>, <B>Noble Energy, Inc</B>., and <B>Sempra Energy</B>, which present this information on their websites. Exxon&#146;s Board and shareholders need comprehensive disclosure to be able to fully evaluate the use
of corporate assets in elections. We urge your support FOR this critical governance reform.&#148; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you vote AGAINST this proposal for the following reasons: </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Company believes disclosure requirements outlined by federal and state laws are adequate. In addition, they are equitable as they require the same level of
disclosure from all participants in the political process. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The Board agrees with the proponent that making political contributions and expenditures with corporate
funds is a legitimate corporate activity. ExxonMobil, like many labor unions, companies, and other entities, engages in the political process by providing financial support to candidates and political organizations, that understand the necessity of
fair and balanced public policy. Corporate political contributions are subject to a strict internal review process that requires them to be approved by the Chairman under the Company&#146;s <I>Political Activities Guidelines</I>, available on our
corporate website. Procedures are routinely verified during internal audits of the Corporation&#146;s political activities. The political contributions of the Corporation, as well as the contributions of the political action committees established
by the Corporation, are reviewed annually with the Board of Directors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil complies fully with all relevant political spending disclosure laws, and also
self-discloses multi-year political contributions to candidates and political organizations in the Political Contributions and Lobbying section of <I>exxonmobil.com</I>.&nbsp;Additional relevant information is found in ExxonMobil&#146;s
<I>Sustainability Report</I>, and websites for federal and state regulatory agencies, and the United States Congress. In addition, political contributions made by the Exxon Mobil Corporation Political Action Committee are reported monthly to the
Federal Election Commission, and are a matter of public record at <I>www.fec.gov</I>. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">To the extent the proponent believes that current law requires inadequate
disclosure from all parties, we believe that the U.S. Congress, Executive Branch, and state and local governments are the appropriate recipients of the proponent&#146;s specific positions on political contribution disclosure laws and any reforms
they seek. ExxonMobil should not be held to a different standard than other groups. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">With the reporting and detail currently provided, the report requested by this
proposal is not necessary. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:arial"><B><A NAME="toc686227_28"></A>Item&nbsp;10 &#150; Report on Lobbying </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">This proposal was submitted by United Steelworkers, 60 Boulevard of the Allies, Pittsburgh, PA 15222, the beneficial owner of 116 shares and lead proponent of a filing
group. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">&#147;<B>Whereas</B>, we believe in full disclosure of ExxonMobil&#146;s direct and indirect lobbying activities and expenditures to assess whether
ExxonMobil&#146;s lobbying is consistent with its expressed goals and in the best interests of shareholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Resolved</B>, the shareholders of ExxonMobil
request the preparation of a report, updated annually, disclosing: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">1.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial; " ALIGN="left">Company policy and procedures governing lobbying, both direct and indirect, and grassroots lobbying communications.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">2.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial; " ALIGN="left">Payments by ExxonMobil used for (a)&nbsp;direct or indirect lobbying or (b)&nbsp;grassroots lobbying communications, in
each case including the amount of the payment and the recipient. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">3.</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial; " ALIGN="left">Description of management&#146;s and the Board&#146;s decision making process and oversight for making payments described
above. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">For purposes of this proposal, a &#145;grassroots lobbying communication&#146; is a communication directed to the general public that
(a)&nbsp;refers to specific legislation or regulation, (b)&nbsp;reflects a view on the legislation or regulation and (c)&nbsp;encourages the recipient of the communication to take action with respect to the legislation or regulation. &#145;Indirect
lobbying&#146; is lobbying engaged in by a trade association or other organization of which ExxonMobil is a member. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Both &#145;direct and indirect lobbying&#146;
and &#145;grassroots lobbying communications&#146; include efforts at the local, state and federal levels. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The report shall be presented to the Audit Committee or other relevant oversight committees and posted on
ExxonMobil&#146;s website. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Supporting Statement </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We encourage
transparency in ExxonMobil&#146;s use of funds to lobby. ExxonMobil spent $99.43&nbsp;million from 2010 &#150; 2017 on federal lobbying. These figures do not include state lobbying expenditures, where ExxonMobil also lobbies but disclosure is uneven
or absent. For example, ExxonMobil spent $3,860,715 on lobbying in California from 2010 &#150; 2017. Exxon also lobbies abroad, reportedly spending between <FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#128;</FONT>3.75m and <FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#128;</FONT>4m on lobbying in Brussels for 2017 (&#145;Revealed: ExxonMobil&#146;s Private Dinner with Cyprus&#146; Top EU Brass,&#146; <I>EU Observer</I>, August&nbsp;12, 2018). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We commend ExxonMobil for ending its membership in the American Legislative Exchange Council (&#145;Exxon Mobil Joins Exodus of Firms from Lobbying Group ALEC,&#146;
<I>Reuters</I>, July&nbsp;12, 2018). However, serious disclosure concerns remain. ExxonMobil belongs to the American Petroleum Institute, Business Roundtable (BRT), Chamber of Commerce and National Association of Manufacturers (NAM), which
altogether spent $260,410,014 on lobbying for 2016 and 2017. Both the BRT and NAM are lobbying against shareholder rights to file resolutions. ExxonMobil does not disclose its memberships in, or payments to, trade associations, or the amounts used
for lobbying. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We are concerned that ExxonMobil&#146;s lack of lobbying disclosure presents reputational risks when its lobbying contradicts company public
positions. For example, ExxonMobil supports the Paris climate agreement, yet was named one of the top three global corporations lobbying against effective climate policy, (&#145;When Corporations Take Credit for Green Deeds Their Lobbying May Tell
Another Story,&#146; <I>The Conversation</I>, July&nbsp;17, 2018), and the Chamber undermined the Paris climate accord (&#145;Paris Pullout Pits Chamber against Some of Its Biggest Members,&#146; <I>Bloomberg</I>, June&nbsp;9, 2017). As
shareholders, we believe that companies should ensure there is alignment between their own positions and their lobbying, including through trade associations.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>The Board recommends you vote AGAINST this proposal for the following reasons: </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The report requested by the proponent is not necessary. The Board fully supports accountability and appropriate transparency and disclosure of lobbying activities and
expenditures. As a result, the Company makes its positions on key issues, lobbying expenses, and specific issues lobbied available to the public. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil has an
established process to determine public policy issues that are important to the Company, which includes reviews by both the Management Committee and the Board. We calibrate our lobbying and advocacy efforts accordingly. Positions on key issues and
grassroots lobbying communications produced by the Corporation are publicly available on the Exxchange website, <I>exxchange.com</I>, ExxonMobil&#146;s advocacy community portal. Our lobbying is aligned with those positions. The Company&#146;s
positions on key issues are also available on <I>exxonmobil.com</I>. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Under our <I>Political Activities Policy </I>and<I> Guidelines,</I> certain employees are
authorized to act on behalf of the Company to execute the political activities of the Company, including lobbying. Lobbying is viewed by the Corporation as a political activity in support of business interests. The policy and guidelines are
viewable, and lobbying activities are described, in the Political Contributions and Lobbying section on <I>exxonmobil.com</I>. Furthermore, ExxonMobil, and where required, its employee lobbyists, file lobby disclosure reports at the state and local
level in accordance with all applicable state and local lobby disclosure laws. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil publicly reports on a quarterly basis to the U.S. Congress our federal
lobbying expenses and the specific issues lobbied. The total figure reported in ExxonMobil&#146;s public Lobbying Disclosure Act filings includes expenses associated with the costs of employee federal lobbying, as well as those portions of payments
to trade associations and other groups that are spent on federal lobbying. All reports are accessible to the general public on the U.S. Senate&#146;s website at <I>www.senate.gov</I>. More recently filed reports are also listed on
<I>exxonmobil.com</I>. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Our contributions to more than 100 U.S.-based organizations are detailed in the <I>Worldwide Contributions and Community Investments: Public
Policy</I> report available at <I>exxonmobil.com</I>. Our contributions do not constitute an endorsement of every policy position or point of view expressed by a recipient organization. As is true of all nonprofit
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:arial; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">
groups we support, an annual evaluation of the merits of each organization is conducted, and we reserve the right to initiate, sustain, or withdraw support at any time as demonstrated by our
actions in 2018 when, for example, we withdrew from the American Legislative Exchange Council. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">These efforts comply fully with the spirit and letter of all federal
and state lobbying disclosure requirements. We believe these existing disclosure laws are appropriately broad and provide the necessary transparency, consistent with that provided by all parties in the political process. ExxonMobil should not be
held to a different standard than other groups engaging in such activity. As such, ExxonMobil believes that the U.S. Congress, Executive Branch, and state and local governments are the appropriate recipients of the proponent&#146;s specific
positions on lobbying disclosure laws, and any reforms they seek. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:arial"><FONT COLOR="#2b4c9b"><B><A NAME="toc686227_29"></A>PAY RATIO </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:20pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The annual total compensation of the CEO of the Corporation for 2018 was $18,810,320. The median of the annual total compensation of all employees of the Corporation
except the CEO for 2018 was $171,375. The ratio of the annual total compensation of the CEO for 2018 to the median of the annual total compensation of all employees was 110:1. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">The median employee was identified as of October&nbsp;1, 2018, based on total taxable wages for the most recently completed prior fiscal year as shown in the
Corporation&#146;s records. No estimates or sampling methodologies were used for this purpose. No <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">cost-of-living</FONT></FONT> adjustments were made, and the taxable wages of
employees employed for less than the full fiscal year were not annualized. &#147;Employees&#148; were defined based on applicable employment and tax laws. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">For
purposes of this disclosure, as permitted by SEC rules, the value of nondiscriminatory benefits is included in annual total compensation of both the median employee and the CEO. These nondiscriminatory benefits are long-term disability, basic life
insurance, accidental death and dismemberment insurance, medical, and dental. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We believe including these benefits provides a more accurate compensation ratio.
Since SEC rules do not require inclusion of these generally available benefits in the Summary Compensation Table, the annual total compensation of the CEO shown above is slightly higher than the Total Compensation shown for the CEO in that table.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">ExxonMobil is a global company with employees in many countries around the world. As permitted by the <I>de minimis </I>exemption under the SEC<I> </I>rules, for
purposes of identifying the median employee we have excluded employees from 41 countries, which represent in aggregate less than 5&nbsp;percent of the Corporation&#146;s total employees. As required, where any employees from a jurisdiction were
excluded, all employees from that jurisdiction were excluded. In total, as detailed in the table below, 2,924 employees were excluded under the <I>de minimis </I>exemption of a total number of 72,619 worldwide employees. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:7.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:arial"><FONT COLOR="#2b4c9b"><B><A NAME="toc686227_30"></A>ADDITIONAL INFORMATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:20pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Other Business </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We are not currently aware of any other business to be acted
on at the annual meeting. Under the laws of New Jersey, where ExxonMobil is incorporated, no business other than procedural matters may be raised at the meeting unless proper notice has been given to the shareholders. If other business is properly
raised, your proxies have authority to vote as they think best, including to adjourn the meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>People With Disabilities </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">We can provide reasonable assistance to help you participate in the meeting if you tell us about your disability and your plans to attend. Please call or write the
Secretary at least two weeks before the meeting at the telephone number, address, or fax number listed under Contact Information on page 7. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Outstanding Shares
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">On February&nbsp;28, 2019, there were 4,233,104,962 shares of common stock outstanding. Each common share has one vote. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>How We Solicit Proxies </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">In addition to this mailing, ExxonMobil officers and
employees may solicit proxies personally, electronically, by telephone, or with additional mailings. ExxonMobil pays the costs of soliciting this proxy. We are paying D.F. King&nbsp;&amp; Co. a fee of $30,000 plus expenses to help with the
solicitation. We also reimburse brokers and other nominees for their expenses in sending these materials to you and getting your voting instructions. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Shareholder Proposals and Director Nominations for Next Year </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Any shareholder
proposal for the annual meeting in 2020 must be sent to the Secretary at the address or fax number of ExxonMobil&#146;s principal executive office listed under Contact Information on page 7. The deadline for receipt of a proposal to be considered
for inclusion in the 2020 proxy statement is 5 p.m. Central Time, on December&nbsp;13, 2019. The deadline for notice of a proposal for which a shareholder will conduct his or her own solicitation is February&nbsp;26, 2020. Upon request, the
Secretary will provide instructions for submitting proposals. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Submissions of nominees for director under the proxy access provisions of our bylaws for the 2020
annual meeting must be submitted in compliance with those bylaws no later than December&nbsp;13, 2019, and no earlier than November&nbsp;13, 2019.&nbsp;Notice of a director nomination other than under proxy access must be submitted in compliance
with the advance notice provisions of our bylaws no later than January&nbsp;30, 2020, and no earlier than December&nbsp;31, 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Duplicate Annual Reports
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">Registered shareholders with multiple accounts may authorize ExxonMobil to discontinue mailing annual reports on an account by calling ExxonMobil Shareholder
Services at the toll-free telephone number listed on page 7 at any time during the year. Beneficial holders should contact their banks, brokers, or other holders of record to discontinue duplicate mailings. At least one account must continue to
receive an annual report. Eliminating these duplicate mailings will not affect receipt of future proxy statements and proxy cards. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial"><B>Shareholders With the Same
Address </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:arial">If you share an address with one or more ExxonMobil shareholders, you may elect to &#147;household&#148; your proxy mailing. This means you will receive
only one set of proxy materials at that address unless one or more shareholders at that address specifically elect to receive separate mailings. Shareholders who participate in householding will continue to receive separate proxy cards. Householding
will not affect dividend check mailings. We will promptly send separate proxy materials to a shareholder at a shared address on request. Shareholders with a shared address may also request us to send separate proxy materials in the future, or to
send a single copy in the future, if we are currently sending multiple copies to the same address. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P>

K.C.&nbsp;Frazier, S.J.&nbsp;Palmisano, S.S&nbsp;Reinemund, and D.W. Woods, or each or any of them, with power of substitution, proxies to act and vote shares of common stock of the undersigned at the 2019 annual meeting of shareholders of Exxon
Mobil Corporation and at any adjournments thereof, as indicated, upon all matters referred to on the reverse side and described in the proxy statement for the meeting and, at their discretion, upon any other matters that may properly come before the
meeting.</P></TD></TR>

book entry) and shares held in the name of the undersigned in the Computershare Investment Plan. This card also provides voting instructions to the applicable trustees for any shares held in the name of the undersigned in the ExxonMobil Savings Plan
and/or a Computershare Investment Plan IRA.</P></TD></TR>
